    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Classic triad (seen in <50% of cases): episodic colicky pain, vomiting, currant jelly stool",
      "Peak age: 6 months to 3 years. Most common cause of bowel obstruction in children this age",
      "Ileocolic junction is the most common site (ileum telescopes into cecum/colon)",
      "Ultrasound is the diagnostic study of choice \u2014 target sign (donut sign) is pathognomonic",
      "Treatment: air-contrast (pneumatic) or hydrostatic enema reduction \u2014 80-95% success rate",
      "Surgical indications: peritonitis, perforation, failed enema reduction, shock, pathologic lead point"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Bowel perforation (free air on X-ray, peritoneal signs \u2014 contraindication to enema reduction)",
      "Pathologic lead point in children >3 years (Meckel diverticulum, lymphoma, polyp \u2014 may need surgery)",
      "Bowel necrosis/ischemia (prolonged intussusception, rising lactate, peritonitis)",
      "Midgut volvulus (bilious vomiting in infant = malrotation with volvulus until proven otherwise)",
      "Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura (purpura on legs/buttocks + abdominal pain + intussusception)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Relying on the 'classic triad' \u2014 majority of patients do NOT have all three features",
      "Missing bilious (green) vomiting as a red flag for obstruction in any child",
      "Not recognizing lethargy between episodes as a worrisome sign (altered mentation from ischemia or shock)",
      "Ordering CT instead of ultrasound (US is more sensitive and avoids radiation in children)",
      "Delaying surgical consultation while awaiting enema \u2014 surgeon should be aware in case reduction fails",
      "Discharging after successful enema reduction without observation \u2014 recurrence rate 5-10% within 72 hours"
    ],
