    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Acute angle-closure glaucoma is an OPHTHALMOLOGIC EMERGENCY \u2014 permanent vision loss within hours if untreated",
      "Classic presentation: painful red eye + blurred vision + halos + nausea/vomiting + mid-dilated fixed pupil + hazy cornea",
      "IOP measurement (tonometry) is diagnostic \u2014 normal is 10-21 mmHg; in AACG typically 40-80+ mmHg",
      "Immediate treatment: topical timolol 0.5% + pilocarpine 2% + topical prednisolone + IV acetazolamide 500mg + IV mannitol if refractory",
      "Pilocarpine constricts the pupil and pulls the iris away from the drainage angle \u2014 but may not work until IOP is lowered first",
      "Definitive treatment: laser peripheral iridotomy (LPI) \u2014 must be performed within 24-48 hours by ophthalmology"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Retrobulbar hemorrhage (trauma + proptosis + vision loss \u2014 lateral canthotomy)",
      "Acute anterior uveitis/iritis (photophobia, small pupil \u2014 opposite of AACG)",
      "Endophthalmitis (post-surgical or endogenous \u2014 hypopyon, severe)",
      "Orbital cellulitis (periorbital swelling, proptosis, pain with eye movement, fever)",
      "Temporal arteritis / GCA (age >50, headache, jaw claudication, vision loss \u2014 check ESR/CRP)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Diagnosing 'migraine with nausea' without examining the eye \u2014 AACG causes headache and vomiting",
      "Not checking pupil response and corneal clarity \u2014 mid-dilated fixed pupil + hazy cornea is pathognomonic",
      "Not measuring IOP \u2014 this is the confirmatory test (most EDs have Tono-Pen or iCare tonometer)",
      "Giving anticholinergics for nausea (ondansetron is fine, but avoid promethazine which can worsen angle closure)",
      "Not treating the fellow eye prophylactically \u2014 if one eye is susceptible, the other usually is too",
      "Delaying ophthalmology consultation \u2014 needs laser iridotomy within 24-48 hours"
    ],
