    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "The 6 P's of acute limb ischemia: Pain, Pallor, Pulselessness, Poikilothermia (cold), Paresthesia, Paralysis \u2014 motor deficit is a LATE and ominous sign",
      "Rutherford classification: I (viable), IIa (marginally threatened \u2014 sensory loss, salvageable with prompt treatment), IIb (immediately threatened \u2014 motor loss, requires emergent intervention), III (irreversible \u2014 mottled, no Doppler signal, amputation)",
      "This patient is Rutherford IIa progressing to IIb \u2014 URGENT revascularization within 6 hours",
      "Embolic vs. thrombotic: sudden onset with no prior claudication + AFib + 'meniscus sign' on CTA = embolic. Thrombotic typically has chronic PAD history with gradual worsening.",
      "Treatment options: surgical embolectomy (Fogarty catheter), catheter-directed thrombolysis, or hybrid approach",
      "HIT HISTORY in this patient \u2014 CANNOT use unfractionated heparin. Use argatroban or bivalirudin for anticoagulation."
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Compartment syndrome (post-reperfusion \u2014 monitor compartment pressures, fasciotomy if >30mmHg)",
      "Reperfusion injury (hyperkalemia, metabolic acidosis, myoglobinuria \u2014 pretreat with IV fluids and bicarb)",
      "Concurrent cardiac thrombus (AFib + low EF = high risk of LV mural thrombus \u2014 echo indicated)",
      "Phlegmasia cerulea dolens (massive DVT with limb ischemia \u2014 different from arterial occlusion but can mimic)",
      "Irreversible ischemia (fixed mottling, muscle rigor, no Doppler signal \u2014 amputation, not revascularization)"
    ],
