    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Hip fractures in the elderly are life-threatening \u2014 1-year mortality is 15-30% after hip fracture",
      "Anticoagulation reversal: supratherapeutic INR must be corrected before surgery. 4-factor PCC (Kcentra) is fastest, vitamin K takes 6-24 hours, FFP is slow and volume-heavy",
      "Surgery within 24-48 hours improves outcomes \u2014 every hour of delay increases complications",
      "'Found down' patients need rhabdomyolysis workup \u2014 CK, renal function, aggressive IV fluids",
      "Delirium is NOT dementia \u2014 acute confusion in a patient with known dementia should trigger search for precipitant (pain, infection, metabolic, medication)",
      "Perioperative management: DVT prophylaxis (challenging with bleeding risk), delirium prevention, early mobilization, fall prevention, bone health optimization"
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Occult head injury (patient was found down with uncertain history \u2014 CT head mandatory even without visible head trauma)",
      "Rhabdomyolysis from prolonged immobility (CK elevation + AKI \u2014 aggressive IVF)",
      "Type 2 MI from demand ischemia (troponin elevation in setting of tachycardia, anemia, stress)",
      "Pressure injuries from prolonged floor time (assess skin over all bony prominences)",
      "C-spine injury (ground-level falls in elderly with osteoporosis can cause cervical fractures)",
      "DVT/PE (immobilization risk \u2014 challenging to prophylax with supratherapeutic INR)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Focusing only on the fracture and missing the medical complexity \u2014 these patients need medical optimization before surgery",
      "Not checking rhabdomyolysis markers in 'found down' patients \u2014 8 hours on a floor can cause significant muscle breakdown",
      "Delaying anticoagulation reversal \u2014 PCC gives rapid reversal to get patient to OR within 24-48 hours",
      "Not recognizing delirium \u2014 attributing confusion to 'baseline dementia' without evaluating for reversible causes",
      "Inadequate pain management \u2014 undertreating pain in the elderly causes delirium and delays surgery",
      "Not involving geriatrics \u2014 co-management by geriatrics reduces mortality and complications in hip fracture patients"
    ],
