    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "The 5 P's: Pain (out of proportion), Pressure (tense compartment), Pain with Passive stretch (most sensitive early finding), Paresthesias (sensory loss \u2014 deep peroneal nerve first web space is earliest), Paralysis (motor loss \u2014 LATE finding). The 6th P \u2014 Pulselessness \u2014 is a VERY LATE finding and its absence does NOT rule out compartment syndrome.",
      "PAIN OUT OF PROPORTION to the injury that does NOT respond to appropriate analgesia is the EARLIEST and MOST IMPORTANT clinical sign.",
      "Compartment pressure measurement: Stryker needle or other manometer. Normal <10mmHg. Absolute pressure >30mmHg or delta pressure (diastolic BP minus compartment pressure) <30mmHg = diagnostic. FASCIOTOMY INDICATED.",
      "FASCIOTOMY is the definitive treatment \u2014 must be performed within 6 hours of symptom onset for best outcomes. After 8 hours, permanent nerve and muscle damage is likely.",
      "The ANTERIOR COMPARTMENT of the leg is the most common location and the DEEP PERONEAL NERVE (sensation first web space, motor toe extension) is the most vulnerable structure.",
      "PULSES ARE PRESENT in compartment syndrome \u2014 this is a critical teaching point. Compartment syndrome is a microvascular problem (capillary perfusion pressure), not a macrovascular problem. Pulses disappear only when compartment pressure exceeds systemic arterial pressure \u2014 this is a pre-amputation finding."
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Vascular injury (check ankle-brachial index if any concern \u2014 CTA if hard signs of vascular injury)",
      "Multi-compartment involvement (leg has 4 compartments: anterior, lateral, deep posterior, superficial posterior \u2014 all must be checked and released if involved)",
      "Bilateral compartment syndrome (bilateral tibial fractures, crush injuries, or prolonged down time)",
      "Myoglobinuric AKI (aggressive IV fluids with UOP target 200-300mL/hr; consider bicarbonate to alkalinize urine)",
      "Missed fracture (ensure complete radiographic evaluation \u2014 tibial plateau, ankle, knee)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Waiting for absent pulses to diagnose compartment syndrome \u2014 PULSES ARE PRESENT until very late. By the time pulses are absent, the leg may be non-salvageable.",
      "Being falsely reassured because narcotics 'should be helping' \u2014 escalating pain requirements despite appropriate analgesia is the RED FLAG",
      "Not performing passive stretch test \u2014 passively extending the toes or dorsiflexing the ankle stretches the anterior compartment muscles; severe pain = positive test",
      "Leaving a tight splint or cast on \u2014 BIVALVE any circumferential dressing immediately. This alone can decrease compartment pressure by 40-60%.",
      "Measuring compartment pressures only once \u2014 if clinical suspicion persists, re-measure. Compartment syndrome is a dynamic, evolving process.",
      "Not releasing ALL affected compartments at fasciotomy \u2014 a four-compartment fasciotomy through two incisions (anterolateral and posteromedial) is standard for leg compartment syndrome"
    ],
