    "keyLearningPoints": [
      "Severe symptomatic hyponatremia (Na <120 with seizure/coma) is a MEDICAL EMERGENCY \u2014 brain edema can cause herniation and death.",
      "EMERGENT TREATMENT for seizure/severe symptoms: HYPERTONIC SALINE (3% NaCl) \u2014 100mL bolus over 10 minutes, can repeat x2 if seizure persists. Goal: raise Na by 4-6 mEq/L in first 1-2 hours to stop cerebral edema progression.",
      "CRITICAL RATE LIMIT: Do NOT correct sodium >8 mEq/L in 24 hours (some guidelines say 10). Overcorrection causes OSMOTIC DEMYELINATION SYNDROME (ODS/central pontine myelinolysis) \u2014 devastating, often permanent neurologic injury.",
      "SIADH diagnosis requires: hyponatremia + low serum osmolality + inappropriately concentrated urine (>100 mOsm) + high urine sodium (>40) + euvolemia + normal thyroid and adrenal function.",
      "This patient has TWO contributing drugs: sertraline (SSRI \u2014 #1 drug cause of SIADH) AND hydrochlorothiazide (impairs free water excretion). Both should be DISCONTINUED.",
      "DESMOPRESSIN CLAMP: if sodium rises too quickly during treatment, give DDAVP 2mcg IV to STOP free water excretion and prevent overcorrection. Simultaneously give D5W to lower sodium back to safe correction rate."
    ],
    "mustNotMiss": [
      "Herniation from cerebral edema (severe hyponatremia causes brain swelling \u2014 emergency if progressing to coma or unilateral signs)",
      "Osmotic Demyelination Syndrome from overcorrection (locked-in syndrome, quadriplegia \u2014 devastating and often permanent. MUST monitor sodium every 2-4 hours during correction)",
      "Status epilepticus (if seizures continue \u2014 treat with both hypertonic saline AND benzodiazepines)",
      "Adrenal insufficiency mimicking SIADH (cortisol must be checked \u2014 both cause euvolemic hyponatremia)",
      "Subarachnoid hemorrhage (can cause SIADH and seizure \u2014 CT head rules out)",
      "Beer potomania or psychogenic polydipsia (extreme water intake overwhelms diluting capacity \u2014 different management)"
    ],
    "commonPitfalls": [
      "Correcting sodium too quickly \u2014 overcorrection >8-10 mEq/24h causes osmotic demyelination syndrome, which is iatrogenic and devastating. Check Na every 2-4 hours.",
      "Using normal saline (0.9% NaCl) for severe symptomatic hyponatremia \u2014 NS may actually WORSEN hyponatremia in SIADH (kidneys excrete the sodium but retain the water). Use 3% hypertonic saline.",
      "Not checking volume status \u2014 SIADH is euvolemic. Hypovolemic hyponatremia (from vomiting, diarrhea) gets normal saline. Hypervolemic (cirrhosis, CHF) gets fluid restriction. Wrong volume assessment \u2192 wrong treatment.",
      "Not identifying the offending drug \u2014 SSRIs are the #1 drug cause of SIADH. Must stop sertraline AND HCTZ.",
      "Over-relying on fluid restriction alone for acute symptomatic hyponatremia \u2014 fluid restriction works for chronic mild SIADH but is TOO SLOW for seizure/severe symptoms. Need hypertonic saline.",
      "Not having a DDAVP rescue plan \u2014 if Na corrects too fast (e.g., SIADH resolves after drug discontinuation and patient auto-corrects), give DDAVP 2mcg IV + D5W to re-lower Na and prevent ODS"
    ],
