          "critical": false,
          "correct": false,
          "phase": 1,
          "teaching": "Topical nasal decongestants (oxymetazoline, xylometazoline) are contraindicated beyond 3 consecutive days \u2014 prolonged use causes rhinitis medicamentosa (rebound nasal congestion from alpha-adrenergic receptor downregulation), creating a dependence cycle that is difficult to break. For allergic rhinitis requiring decongestant therapy, oral pseudoephedrine or intranasal ipratropium are safer alternatives. Oral decongestants avoid the rebound risk entirely.",
